{"title_page": "Jerome Vered", "text_new": "{{short description|American writer and game show contestant}}\n'''Jerome Vered''' (born March 13, 1958) is a [[Studio City, California]] writer, publicly known for his record-setting success as a contestant on the U.S. television [[game show]] ''[[Jeopardy!]]''\n\n==Biography==\nVered graduated from [[Harvard College]] and the [[University of Southern California|USC]] School of Cinema-Television.<ref name=latimes/> He took the ''Jeopardy'' test four times (in 1987, 1988, 1989, and 1990) before being called to the show as an alternate in March 1991. He was not used in any of that day's tapings, but he did return the next year, and became a five-day champion,<ref name=seattle/> with winnings totaling $96,801, second to [[Frank Spangenberg]]'s $102,597. During that run, he shattered the one-day record for dollar winnings, earning $34,000 in one episode.<ref name=latimes>{{cite news|first=David|last=Wharton|title=And the Question Is ... Will a Studio City Writer Top the ''Jeopardy!'' Winnings Total Tonight?|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=May 22, 1992|page=19A}}</ref>\n\nAfter his five-day run, Vered returned for the 1992 [[Jeopardy! Tournament of Champions|''Jeopardy!'' Tournament of Champions]], finishing in third place and winning $7,500.<ref name=seattle>Veronique de Turenne. \"Jeopardy winners say it's nice work if you can get it\". ''Seattle Post-Intelligencer''. November 27, 1992. p. 39</ref>\n\nIn the 2005 [[Jeopardy! Ultimate Tournament of Champions|Ultimate Tournament of Champions]], Vered won five games to advance to a three-game final match against fellow ''Jeopardy!'' record-setters [[Ken Jennings]] and [[Brad Rutter]]. Vered finished in third place, earning $250,000.<ref>{{cite news |author=[[Lawrence Van Gelder]] |coauthors= |title=Arts, Briefly: 'Jeopardy!' Titans Battle  |url=https://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=FA0810F93B5D0C748EDDAC0894DD404482 |quote=Mr. Jennings's second-place finish paid him $500,000, and the third place finisher, Jerome Vered, received $250,000.  |work=[[New York Times]] |date=May 27, 2005 |accessdate=2010-10-04 }}</ref>  Of the three finalists, he was the only one not to get a bye in the tournament, as Rutter got a bye into the second round and Jennings got a bye into the finals.\n\nVered again appeared on ''Jeopardy!'' on February 7, 2014 as a contestant in the [[Jeopardy! Battle of the Decades|Battle of the Decades]] tournament. He faced [[List of Jeopardy! contestants#Tom Cubbage|Tom Cubbage]] and [[List of Jeopardy! contestants#Bob Verini|Bob Verini]] in a \"1980s bracket\" game, failed to advance to the next round, winning $5,000 when he finished second to Cubbage. At that time, this placed Vered behind Rutter and Jennings, respectively, as the third highest-earning contestant in ''Jeopardy!'' history, having won a total of $359,301 across his original five wins, the 1992 Tournament of Champions, 2005's Ultimate Tournament of Champions, and 2014's Battle of the Decades.\n\nAlthough Vered is best known for his ''Jeopardy!'' prowess, he has also dominated in other quiz-show formats, including ''[[Win Ben Stein's Money]]'', during which he recorded the first-ever sweep, and became the first to take home the full $5,000 of [[Ben Stein]]'s money.<ref>Bob Harris. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=sI2FAAAAIAAJ&q=%22Win+Ben+Stein%27s+Money%22+impressively&dq=%22Win+Ben+Stein%27s+Money%22+impressively&client=firefox-a Prisoner of Trebekistan]''. Crown Publishers, 2006. p. 221</ref> He would later become a researcher on the show's staff.<ref>\"[http://www.triviahalloffame.com/vered.php Jerome Vered: the great Jeopardy asterisk]\". Trivia Hall of Fame. Retrieved on June 20, 2013.</ref> Vered's game show winnings thus total $364,301.\n\nIn 2009, Vered was used as a Phone-a-Friend lifeline on Who Wants to Be a Millionaire? 10th Anniversary when Ken Basin, from Los Angeles, CA, called him for help on his $500,000 question on the final episode of the 10th Anniversary.\n\nIn 2009, Vered became the first American to crack the top 10 at a [[World Quizzing Championship]] with an eighth-place finish.<ref>IQA.be. ''[http://www.iqa.be/iqa_wqc_uk2009.htm-a WQC2009 Results]{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}''.</ref>\n\nIn 2017, he competed in a Los Angeles citywide pub tournament as part of Team of Enchantment (along with Brian Fodera, Matthew Frost, Pam Mueller, Brad Rutter and Hans von Walter), taking home his share of a $10,000 prize.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.triviahalloffame.com/vered.aspx Article at Paul Paquet's triviahalloffame]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20091119205205/http://www.wqc2009.com/ WQC 2009]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box | before = Mark Born | title = Biggest ''[[Jeopardy!]]'' winners by season | years = 1991-1992 | after = Edward Schiffer}}\n{{succession box | before = Mark Born | title = Biggest one-day winners on ''[[Jeopardy!]]'' by season | years = 1991-1992 | after = Mike Boyd}}\n{{succession box | before = Lou Pryor | title = [[Jeopardy! Tournament of Champions|''Jeopardy!'' Tournament of Champions]] second runner-up | years = 1992 | after = Marilyn Kneeland}}\n{{succession box | before = [[Frank Spangenberg]] <br> $30,600 <br> 1990 | title = Biggest one-day winner on ''[[Jeopardy!]]'' <br> $34,000 | years = 1992 | after = Ben Sternberg <br>$38,400 <br>2002 <br> (after clue values doubled) <br> [[Ken Jennings]] <br> $75,000 <br> 2004 <br> (would be halved prior to clue values doubling)}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Jeopardy!}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vered, Jerome}}\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Studio City, Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Jeopardy! contestants]]\n[[Category:Contestants on American game shows]]\n[[Category:Harvard College alumni]]\n[[Category:USC School of Cinematic Arts alumni]]\n[[Category:American male writers]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American writer and game show contestant}}\n'''Jerome Vered''' (born March 13, 1958) is a [[Studio City, California]] writer, publicly known for his record-setting success as a contestant on the U.S. television [[game show]] ''[[Jeopardy!]]''\n\n==Biography==\nVered graduated from [[Harvard College]] and the [[University of Southern California|USC]] School of Cinema-Television.<ref name=latimes/> He took the ''Jeopardy'' test four times (in 1987, 1988, 1989, and 1990) before being called to the show as an alternate in March 1991. He was not used in any of that day's tapings, but he did return the next year, and became a five-day champion,<ref name=seattle/> with winnings totaling $96,801, second to [[Frank Spangenberg]]'s $102,597. During that run, he shattered the one-day record for dollar winnings, earning $34,000 in one episode.<ref name=latimes>{{cite news|first=David|last=Wharton|title=And the Question Is ... Will a Studio City Writer Top the ''Jeopardy!'' Winnings Total Tonight?|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=May 22, 1992|page=19A}}</ref>\n\nAfter his five-day run, Vered returned for the 1992 [[Jeopardy! Tournament of Champions|''Jeopardy!'' Tournament of Champions]], finishing in third place and winning $7,500.<ref name=seattle>Veronique de Turenne. \"Jeopardy winners say it's nice work if you can get it\". ''Seattle Post-Intelligencer''. November 27, 1992. p. 39</ref>\n\nIn the 2005 [[Jeopardy! Ultimate Tournament of Champions|Ultimate Tournament of Champions]], Vered won five games to advance to a three-game final match against fellow ''Jeopardy!'' record-setters [[Ken Jennings]] and [[Brad Rutter]]. Vered finished in third place, earning $250,000.<ref>{{cite news |author=[[Lawrence Van Gelder]] |coauthors= |title=Arts, Briefly: 'Jeopardy!' Titans Battle  |url=https://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=FA0810F93B5D0C748EDDAC0894DD404482 |quote=Mr. Jennings's second-place finish paid him $500,000, and the third place finisher, Jerome Vered, received $250,000.  |work=[[New York Times]] |date=May 27, 2005 |accessdate=2010-10-04 }}</ref>  Of the three finalists, he was the only one not to get a bye in the tournament, as Rutter got a bye into the second round and Jennings got a bye into the finals.\n\nVered again appeared on ''Jeopardy!'' on February 7, 2014 as a contestant in the [[Jeopardy! Battle of the Decades|Battle of the Decades]] tournament. He faced [[List of Jeopardy! contestants#Tom Cubbage|Tom Cubbage]] and [[List of Jeopardy! contestants#Bob Verini|Bob Verini]] in a \"1980s bracket\" game, failed to advance to the next round, winning $5,000 when he finished second to Cubbage. At that time, this placed Vered behind Rutter and Jennings, respectively, as the third highest-earning contestant in ''Jeopardy!'' history, having won a total of $359,301 across his original five wins, the 1992 Tournament of Champions, 2005's Ultimate Tournament of Champions, and 2014's Battle of the Decades.\n\nAlthough Vered is best known for his ''Jeopardy!'' prowess, he has also dominated in other quiz-show formats, including ''[[Win Ben Stein's Money]]'', during which he recorded the first-ever sweep, and became the first to take home the full $5,000 of [[Ben Stein]]'s money.<ref>Bob Harris. ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=sI2FAAAAIAAJ&q=%22Win+Ben+Stein%27s+Money%22+impressively&dq=%22Win+Ben+Stein%27s+Money%22+impressively&client=firefox-a Prisoner of Trebekistan]''. Crown Publishers, 2006. p. 221</ref> He would later become a researcher on the show's staff.<ref>\"[http://www.triviahalloffame.com/vered.php Jerome Vered: the great Jeopardy asterisk]\". Trivia Hall of Fame. Retrieved on June 20, 2013.</ref> Vered's game show winnings thus total $364,301.\n\nIn 2009, Vered was used as a Phone-a-Friend lifeline on Who Wants to Be a Millionaire? 10th Anniversary when Ken Basin, from Los Angeles, CA, called him for help on his $500,000 question on the final episode of the 10th Anniversary.\n\nIn 2009, Vered became the first American to crack the top 10 at a [[World Quizzing Championship]] with an eighth-place finish.<ref>IQA.be. ''[http://www.iqa.be/iqa_wqc_uk2009.htm-a WQC2009 Results]{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}''.</ref>\n\nIn 2017, he competed in a Los Angeles citywide pub tournament as part of Team of Enchantment (along with Brian Fodera, Matthew Frost, Pam Mueller, Brad Rutter and Hans von Walter), taking home his share of a $10,000 prize.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.triviahalloffame.com/vered.aspx Article at Paul Paquet's triviahalloffame]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20091119205205/http://www.wqc2009.com/ WQC 2009]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box | before = Mark Born | title = Biggest ''[[Jeopardy!]]'' winners by season | years = 1991-1992 | after = Edward Schiffer}}\n{{succession box | before = Mark Born | title = Biggest one-day winners on ''[[Jeopardy!]]'' by season | years = 1991-1992 | after = Mike Boyd}}\n{{succession box | before = Lou Pryor | title = [[Jeopardy! Tournament of Champions|''Jeopardy!'' Tournament of Champions]] second runner-up | years = 1992 | after = Marilyn Kneeland}}\n{{succession box | before = [[Frank Spangenberg]] <br> $30,600 <br> 1990 | title = Biggest one-day winner on ''[[Jeopardy!]]'' <br> $34,000 | years = 1992 | after = Ben Sternberg <br>$38,400 <br>2002 <br> (after clue values doubled) <br> [[Ken Jennings]] <br> $75,000 <br> 2004 <br> (would be halved prior to clue values doubling)}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Jeopardy!}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vered, Jerome}}\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Studio City, Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Jeopardy! contestants]]\n[[Category:Contestants on American game shows]]\n[[Category:Harvard College alumni]]\n[[Category:USC School of Cinematic Arts alumni]]\n[[Category:American male writers]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExte