{"title_page": "Jerome T. Murphy", "text_new": "{{for|the American football player|Jerome Murphy}}\n{{short description|American professor}}\n{{Infobox writer\n|image = Jerry head-shot 1(4) (27903183832).jpg\n|imagesize =\n|name  = Jerome T. Murphy\n|birth_date = {{Birth year and age|1938}}\n|birth_place = New York City, NY\n|caption = Jerome T. Murphy\n|alma_mater = Columbia & Harvard\n|nationality = American\n}}\n\n'''Jerome T. (Jerry) Murphy''' (born 1938) is the Harold Howe II Professor of Education Emeritus and Dean Emeritus at the [[Harvard Graduate School of Education]].<ref>https://www.gse.harvard.edu/about/history/deans/murphy</ref> Jerry Murphy's current [[Education|teaching]] and [[research]] focuses on the inner life of education leaders and how to find meaning and vitality in the midst of stress and strain.<ref>https://www.gse.harvard.edu/news/uk/09/01/leadership-trap</ref>\n\n== Life and career ==\nMurphy has two degrees from Columbia University; a B.A. from Columbia College and a M.A. from Teachers College.<ref>https://www.tc.columbia.edu/articles/1998/april/academic-homecoming/</ref><ref>http://spectatorarchive.library.columbia.edu/cgi-bin/columbia?a=d&d=cs19600226-01.2.5&e=-------en-20--1--txt-txIN------</ref>\nHe also has an Ed.D. from the Harvard Graduate School of Education.<ref>https://www.gse.harvard.edu/faculty/jerome-murphyg/</ref>\n\nMurphy started his career with two years as a [[State school|public school]] math [[teacher]] in [[Manhasset, New York]]. He then worked for the [[Federal government of the United States|federal government]] as part of the [[War on Poverty]]. He was part of a team that helped develop the [[Elementary and Secondary Education Act]] of 1965,<ref>https://www.rand.org/content/dam/rand/pubs/reports/2009/R1292.pdf</ref> and he later spent a year as the Associate Director of the [[White House Fellows]] program and Associate Staff Director of the National Advisory Council on the Education of Disadvantaged Children.<ref name=\"about\">https://www.gse.harvard.edu/faculty/jerome-murphy</ref>\n\nAfter the election of [[Richard Nixon]], Murphy left his position and became a [[Doctorate|doctoral]] student at the [[Harvard Graduate School of Education]], where he has been ever since.<ref>https://www.gse.harvard.edu/news-tags/jerry-murphy</ref><ref name=\"about\" />\n\nMurphy has studied and written about the everyday realities of [[education]]. He became a specialist in the [[politics]] of [[education]], with a focus on [[Public policy|government policy]], program implementation and evaluation, organizational leadership, and [[Qualitative research|qualitative methodology]]. Murphy conducted some of the earliest studies of the implementation of the [[Great Society]] education programs and the role of the states in educational policy and governance, and contributed to novel data-collection techniques in educational evaluation.<ref name=\"step down\">http://www.gse.harvard.edu/news/00/06/jerry-murphy-step-down-dean-next-summer</ref> He has written books and articles about these topics as well as about schools of education, about the lives of education leaders, and about the changing roles of [[Superintendent (education)|school superintendents]] and [[State education agency|chief state school officers]].\n\nNotable Published Works:\n*''The Unheroic Side of Leadership: Notes from the Swamp''. [[San Francisco]], CA In The Jossey-Bass Reader on Educational Leadership (pp.&nbsp;51\u201362) John Wiley & Sons, Inc. 2007\n*''Embracing Confusion: What Leaders Do When They Don\u2019t Know What to Do''. (co-author) [[Phi Delta Kappan]], Volume 86, No. 5, January 2005, (pp.&nbsp;358\u2013366)\n*''State Leadership in Education: On Being a Chief State School Officer''. ([[Editing|Editor]]) [[Washington, DC]]: Institute for Educational Leadership, 1980\n*''Getting the Facts: A Fieldwork Guide for Evaluators and Policy Analysts''. [[Santa Monica, California|Santa Monica, CA]]: Goodyear Publishing Company, 1980\n*''The Education Bureaucracies Implement Novel Policy: The Politics of Title I ESEA 1965-1972''. [[Boston]], MA: [[Little, Brown and Company]] Policy and Politics in America edited by Allan P. Sindler, 1973\n\nMurphy has also examined educational [[policy]] and practices in [[Australia]], [[China]], [[Colombia]], [[England]], [[Japan]], and [[South Africa]], and has given presentations at international exchange meetings in [[Denmark]], [[Israel]], [[Norway]], [[Russia]], [[Saudi Arabia]], [[Sweden]], and [[Thailand]].\n\nFor nearly 20 years, Murphy was a full-time administrator at the [[Harvard Graduate School of Education]], first as associate dean from 1982 to 1991 and then as [[dean (education)|dean]] from 1992 to 2001. As dean, Murphy led the development of new initiatives in [[Educational technology|learning technologies]], arts education, [[neuroscience]], and school leadership. He also led a [[Fundraising|capital campaign]], which raised almost twice the anticipated goal. For his efforts at the [[Harvard Graduate School of Education]] he was honored with an [[Financial endowment|endowed chair]] named after him.<ref>http://news.harvard.edu/gazette/2000/06.08/murphy1.html</ref><ref name=\"step down\" />\n\nIn 2016 Harvard Education Press published Murphy\u2019s book, ''Dancing in the Rain:  Leading with Compassion, Vitality, and Mindfulness in Education'', a guide for education leaders in applying mindfulness and self-compassion for developing inner strengths.<ref>http://hepg.org/hep-home/books/dancing-in-the-rain</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Murphy, Jerome T}}\n[[Category:1938 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male writers]]\n[[Category:Harvard Graduate School of Education alumni]]\n[[Category:Teachers College, Columbia University alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard Graduate School of Education faculty]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American professor}}\n{{for|the American football player|Jerome Murphy}}\n{{Infobox writer\n|image = Jerry head-shot 1(4) (27903183832).jpg\n|imagesize =\n|name  = Jerome T. Murphy\n|birth_date = {{Birth year and age|1938}}\n|birth_place = New York City, NY\n|caption = Jerome T. Murphy\n|alma_mater = Columbia & Harvard\n|nationality = American\n}}\n\n'''Jerome T. (Jerry) Murphy''' (born 1938) is the Harold Howe II Professor of Education Emeritus and Dean Emeritus at the [[Harvard Graduate School of Education]].<ref>https://www.gse.harvard.edu/about/history/deans/murphy</ref> Jerry Murphy's current [[Education|teaching]] and [[research]] focuses on the inner life of education leaders and how to find meaning and vitality in the midst of stress and strain.<ref>https://www.gse.harvard.edu/news/uk/09/01/leadership-trap</ref>\n\n== Life and career ==\nMurphy has two degrees from Columbia University; a B.A. from Columbia College and a M.A. from Teachers College.<ref>https://www.tc.columbia.edu/articles/1998/april/academic-homecoming/</ref><ref>http://spectatorarchive.library.columbia.edu/cgi-bin/columbia?a=d&d=cs19600226-01.2.5&e=-------en-20--1--txt-txIN------</ref>\nHe also has an Ed.D. from the Harvard Graduate School of Education.<ref>https://www.gse.harvard.edu/faculty/jerome-murphyg/</ref>\n\nMurphy started his career with two years as a [[State school|public school]] math [[teacher]] in [[Manhasset, New York]]. He then worked for the [[Federal government of the United States|federal government]] as part of the [[War on Poverty]]. He was part of a team that helped develop the [[Elementary and Secondary Education Act]] of 1965,<ref>https://www.rand.org/content/dam/rand/pubs/reports/2009/R1292.pdf</ref> and he later spent a year as the Associate Director of the [[White House Fellows]] program and Associate Staff Director of the National Advisory Council on the Education of Disadvantaged Children.<ref name=\"about\">https://www.gse.harvard.edu/faculty/jerome-murphy</ref>\n\nAfter the election of [[Richard Nixon]], Murphy left his position and became a [[Doctorate|doctoral]] student at the [[Harvard Graduate School of Education]], where he has been ever since.<ref>https://www.gse.harvard.edu/news-tags/jerry-murphy</ref><ref name=\"about\" />\n\nMurphy has studied and written about the everyday realities of [[education]]. He became a specialist in the [[politics]] of [[education]], with a focus on [[Public policy|government policy]], program implementation and evaluation, organizational leadership, and [[Qualitative research|qualitative methodology]]. Murphy conducted some of the earliest studies of the implementation of the [[Great Society]] education programs and the role of the states in educational policy and governance, and contributed to novel data-collection techniques in educational evaluation.<ref name=\"step down\">http://www.gse.harvard.edu/news/00/06/jerry-murphy-step-down-dean-next-summer</ref> He has written books and articles about these topics as well as about schools of education, about the lives of education leaders, and about the changing roles of [[Superintendent (education)|school superintendents]] and [[State education agency|chief state school officers]].\n\nNotable Published Works:\n*''The Unheroic Side of Leadership: Notes from the Swamp''. [[San Francisco]], CA In The Jossey-Bass Reader on Educational Leadership (pp.&nbsp;51\u201362) John Wiley & Sons, Inc. 2007\n*''Embracing Confusion: What Leaders Do When They Don\u2019t Know What to Do''. (co-author) [[Phi Delta Kappan]], Volume 86, No. 5, January 2005, (pp.&nbsp;358\u2013366)\n*''State Leadership in Education: On Being a Chief State School Officer''. ([[Editing|Editor]]) [[Washington, DC]]: Institute for Educational Leadership, 1980\n*''Getting the Facts: A Fieldwork Guide for Evaluators and Policy Analysts''. [[Santa Monica, California|Santa Monica, CA]]: Goodyear Publishing Company, 1980\n*''The Education Bureaucracies Implement Novel Policy: The Politics of Title I ESEA 1965-1972''. [[Boston]], MA: [[Little, Brown and Company]] Policy and Politics in America edited by Allan P. Sindler, 1973\n\nMurphy has also examined educational [[policy]] and practices in [[Australia]], [[China]], [[Colombia]], [[England]], [[Japan]], and [[South Africa]], and has given presentations at international exchange meetings in [[Denmark]], [[Israel]], [[Norway]], [[Russia]], [[Saudi Arabia]], [[Sweden]], and [[Thailand]].\n\nFor nearly 20 years, Murphy was a full-time administrator at the [[Harvard Graduate School of Education]], first as associate dean from 1982 to 1991 and then as [[dean (education)|dean]] from 1992 to 2001. As dean, Murphy led the development of new initiatives in [[Educational technology|learning technologies]], arts education, [[neuroscience]], and school leadership. He also led a [[Fundraising|capital campaign]], which raised almost twice the anticipated goal. For his efforts at the [[Harvard Graduate School of Education]] he was honored with an [[Financial endowment|endowed chair]] named after him.<ref>http://news.harvard.edu/gazette/2000/06.08/murphy1.html</ref><ref name=\"step down\" />\n\nIn 2016 Harvard Education Press published Murphy\u2019s book, ''Dancing in the Rain:  Leading with Compassion, Vitality, and Mindfulness in Education'', a guide for education leaders in applying mindfulness and self-compassion for developing inner strengths.<ref>http://hepg.org/hep-home/books/dancing-in-the-rain</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Murphy, Jerome T}}\n[[Category:1938 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male writers]]\n[[Category:Harvard Graduate School of Education alumni]]\n[[Category:Teachers College, Columbia University alumni]]\n[[Category:Harvard Graduate School of Education faculty]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jerome_T._Murphy"}
{"title_page": "Jerome Starkey", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2011}}\n'''Jerome Starkey''' (born 1981, [[London]]) is an [[English people|English]] [[journalist]], [[Documentary film|broadcaster]] and [[motivational speaker]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alternatives.org.uk/event/co-founder-extinction-rebellion-dna-skeena-rathor-multi-speaker-event-navigating-through|title=Co-founder of the Extinction Rebellion DNA - Skeena Rathor in multi speaker event - Navigating through an urgent time of change|last=UK|first=Alternatives|date=2019-11-12|website=www.alternatives.org.uk|language=en|access-date=2019-11-18}}</ref> best known for covering [[war]]s and the [[Natural environment|environment]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.frontlineclub.com/awards2010/|title=2010|website=Frontline Club|language=en|access-date=2019-11-01}}</ref> He challenged [[United States Armed Forces|US forces]] over [[Civilian casualties in the war in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|civilian casualties]] in [[Afghanistan|Afghanistsan]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2010/03/27/nato-tries-to-silence-jou_n_515652.html|title=NATO Tries To Silence Journalist Jerome Starkey Over Afghan Slayings (VIDEO)|date=2010-05-26|website=HuffPost UK|language=en|access-date=2019-11-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.niemanwatchdog.org/index.cfm?backgroundid=00440&fuseaction=background.view|title=U.S.-led forces in Afghanistan are committing atrocities, lying, and getting away with it|publisher=}}</ref> and was deported from [[Kenya]] in 2017<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mobile.nation.co.ke/news/Police-deport-British-journalist-/1950946-3481188-7ojd43z/index.html|title=Police deport British journalist Jerome Starkey|last=App|first=Daily Nation|website=mobile.nation.co.ke|language=en|access-date=2019-11-01}}</ref> after reporting on state-sponsored [[corruption]] and [[Extrajudicial killing|extra-judicial killings]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/kenyan-beauty-spot-blighted-by-all-the-bodies-washing-up-h3vq8v39f|title=Kenyan beauty spot blighted by 'all the bodies washing up'|last=|first=|date=15 July 2016|newspaper=The Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nStarkey grew up in [[London]] and won an academic [[scholarship]] to attend [[Stowe School]] in Buckinghamshire.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/india/struck-by-a-rocket-that-killed-his-brother-boy-brings-out-the-best-in-man/cid/324792|title=Struck by a rocket that killed his brother, boy brings out the best in man|website=www.telegraphindia.com|language=en|access-date=2019-11-01}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nAfter graduating from [[Newcastle University]] with a degree in [[English literature]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.questia.com/newspaper/1G1-106280707/an-extra-degree-of-debt|title=\"An Extra Degree of Debt\" - The Journal (Newcastle, England), August 5, 2003 {{!}} Online Research Library: Questia|website=www.questia.com|access-date=2019-11-01}}</ref> he joined [[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]] in 2003 as a gradaute trainee.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.standard.co.uk/lifestyle/esmagazine/despatches-from-the-front-line-6451466.html|title=Despatches from the front line|date=2011-10-07|website=Evening Standard|language=en|access-date=2019-11-01}}</ref>\n\n=== Afghanistan ===\nIn 2006 he moved to [[Kabul]], Afghanistan to write [[propaganda]] for [[NATO|Nato]]'s [[International Security Assistance Force]]<ref name=\"Satterlee\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2008/jun/09/afghanistan-nato|title=Dispatches from the Afghan front|last=Satterlee|first=Saundra|date=2008-06-09|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-11-01|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> (Isaf). He served with the Combined Joint [[Psychological warfare|Psy-Ops]] Taskforce (CJPOTF) which produced a fortnightly newspaper called ''Sada-e Azadi'', or Voice of Freedom in [[Dari language|Dari]]. He resigned after six months, complaining that the newspaper was \"terrible\".<ref name=\"Satterlee\"/> Later he wrote in [[The Times]] how ''Sada-e Azadi'' was sold by the kilogram as scrap before it could reach readers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/natos-voice-is-stifled-as-propaganda-newspaper-ends-up-as-food-wrapping-td3dcwl2jcv|title=Nato's voice is stifled as propaganda newspaper ends up as food wrapping|last=story|first=Jerome Starkey: Behind the|date=2009-11-12|work=The Times|access-date=2019-11-01|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref>\n\nStarkey returned to Kabul as a [[Freelancer|freelance journalist]]. From 2008 until 2010 he worked for a range of broadcasters and newspapers including [[Sky News]], [[France 24]], ''[[The Scotsman]]'' and ''[[The Independent]]''. At ''[[The Independent]]'' he led a successful campaign to free a student journalist<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/free-at-last-student-in-hiding-after-karzais-intervention-1782909.html|title=Free at last: Student in hiding after Karzai's intervention|author=Kim Sengupta in Kabul|date=22 October 2011|work=The Independent}}</ref> [[Sayed Pervez Kambaksh]], who had been sentenced to death for [[blasphemy]].\n\n==== Civilian Casualties ====\nStarkey claimed that he was [[Blacklisting|black-listed]] by the military in Afghanistan as a result of his work on civilian casualties.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stripes.com/blogs/ombudsman/ombudsman-1.8931/reporter-complains-of-blacklisting-in-afghanistan-1.8946|title=Reporter complains of blacklisting in Afghanistan|work=Stars and Stripes}}</ref><ref>http://www.truth-out.org/where-are-this-wars-heroes-military-and-journalistic57406</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/robert-greenwald/rethink-afghanistan-why-i_b_527439.html#|title=Rethink Afghanistan: Independent Media Stands Up to Pentagon Propaganda|date=6 April 2010|work=The Huffington Post}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010 his investigation into a [[Night raid on Narang|Night Raid on Narang]], in Kunar Province, eastern Afghanistan, led [[International Security Assistance Force|NATO\u2019s International Security Assistance Force]] to admit it had killed eight schoolboys by mistake.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/nato-admits-that-deaths-of-8-boys-were-a-mistake-6hbmv3ljmj6|title=Nato admits that deaths of 8 boys were a mistake|last=Kabul|first=Jerome Starkey|date=2010-02-25|work=The Times|access-date=2019-11-01|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref>\n\nThe previous year he linked the newly formed [[United States Marine Corps Forces Special Operations Command|Marine Special Operations Command]] (MASROC) to three of the worst civilian casualty incidents in Afghanistan's recent history<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/rumsfelds-renegade-unit-blamed-for-afghan-deaths-1685704.html|title=Rumsfeld's renegade unit blamed for Afghan deaths|date=2009-05-16|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2019-11-01}}</ref> including the [[Granai airstrike|Granai Airstrike]] in [[Bala Baluk massacre|Bala Balouk]], the [[Azizabad airstrike|Azizabad Airstrike]] in [[Herat Province|Herat province]] and the [[2007 Shinwar shooting|Shinwar Massacre]] in [[Nangarhar Province|Nangahar province]].\n\n===== Gardez night raid =====\nIn 2010, together with his colleagues Shoib Najafizada and Jeremy Kelly, Starkey exposed a [[cover-up]] by [[United States Army Special Forces|US Special Forces]] after an operation known as the [[Raid on Khataba]]<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/afghanistan/article7092604.ece|title=Login|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theintercept.com/2016/06/01/pentagon-special-ops-killing-of-pregnant-afghan-women-was-appropriate-use-of-force/|title=Pentagon: Special Ops Killing of Pregnant Afghan Women Was \"Appropriate\" Use of Force: Pentagon: Special Ops Killing of Pregnant Afghan Women Was \"Appropriate\" Use of Force|last=Scahill|first=Jeremy|date=2016-06-01|website=The Intercept|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/afghans-us-troops-covered-up-civilian-deaths/|title=Afghans: U.S. Troops \"Covered-Up\" Civilian Deaths|website=www.cbsnews.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/nato-covered-up-botched-night-raid-in-afghanistan-that-killed-five-fc9n5g92gbj|title=Nato 'covered up' botched night raid in Afghanistan that killed five|last=Khataba|first=Jerome Starkey|date=2010-03-13|work=The Times|access-date=2019-11-01|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref> which inspired the [[Academy Awards|Oscar]]-nominated documentary [[Dirty Wars]].\n\nDuring the raid, on 12 February 2010, unidentified special forces soldiers killed five innocent people including two pregnant women, a teenage girl engaged to be married and two brothers who worked for the local government in [[Paktia Province|Paktia]] province in [[Eastern Afghanistan Operations|eastern Afghanistan]].<ref name=\":0\" /> All of the victims were from the same family. Initially the soldiers said the women were victims of a triple [[Honor killing|honour killing]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://afghanistan.blogs.cnn.com/2010/02/12/bound-gagged-bodies-of-women-found/|title=Bodies believed to be 'honor killing' victims|language=en|access-date=2019-11-01}}</ref> They said they discovered the women's bodies \"tied up, gagged and killed\"<ref name=\"dvidshub.net\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dvidshub.net/news/45240/joint-force-operating-gardez-makes-gruesome-discovery|title=Joint force operating in Gardez makes gruesome discovery|website=DVIDS|language=en|access-date=2019-11-01}}</ref> and that the dead men were [[Insurgency|insurgents]].<ref name=\"dvidshub.net\"/>\n\nWhen Starkey challenged Nato's account they accused him of lying.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.military-world.net/Afghanistan/3502.html | title=ISAF Rejects Cover up Allegation &#124; Military-World Website}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/04/06/world/asia/06afghan.html|title=Afghan Investigators Say U.S. Troops Tried to Cover Up Evidence in Botched Raid|last=Jr|first=Richard A. Oppel|date=2010-04-05|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-11-01|last2=Wafa|first2=Abdul Waheed|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> However, four weeks later [[William H. McRaven]], the commander of America's [[Joint Special Operations Command]] ([[Joint Special Operations Command|JSOC]]), admitted his soldiers were resopnsible.<ref name=\"Gardez\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/us-army-chief-begs-afghans-to-forgive-k9lkmmr5cjx|title=US army chief begs Afghans to forgive|last=Gardez|first=Jerome Starkey, Khataba|date=2010-04-09|work=The Times|access-date=2019-11-01|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref> [[William H. McRaven|McRaven]] travelled to the family's compound, outside [[Gardez]] and offered to sacrifice a sheep outside their door in a ritual act of [[Nanawatai]], to seek their forgiveness.<ref name=\"Gardez\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/WN/Afghanistan/special-forces-apologize-afghan-civilian-deaths-sheep/story?id=10320603|title=Apologizing for Afghan Deaths With Sheep?|website=ABC News|language=en|access-date=2019-11-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.csmonitor.com/World/Asia-South-Central/2010/0408/US-military-offers-sheep-in-apology-for-Afghanistan-deaths|title=US military offers sheep in apology for Afghanistan deaths|date=2010-04-08|work=Christian Science Monitor|access-date=2019-11-01|issn=0882-7729}}</ref>\n\n==== Close calls ====\nIn 2010, Jerome was nearly killed during an [[Embedded journalism|embed]] with British troops in [[Helmand Province]] when an [[Improvised explosive device]] (IED) exploded fewer than 10 metres in front of him.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/news/world/asia/afghanistan/article2775671.ece|title=Final, fatal step of 'a really brilliant bloke'|newspaper=The Times|date=21 October 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/top-stories/2010/10/22/30-feet-from-the-brutal-reality-of-the-afghan-war-death-of-a-soldier-115875-22650096/|title=30 feet from the brutal reality of the Afghan war: Death of a soldier|author=mirror Administrator|date=22 October 2010|work=mirror}}</ref> The explosion, inside a designated safe area which had recently been cleared by the [[Royal Engineers]], killed Corporal David Barnsdale<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mod.uk/DefenceInternet/DefenceNews/MilitaryOperations/CorporalDavidBarnsdaleKilledInAfghanistan.htm|title=Corporal David Barnsdale killed in Afghanistan|publisher=}}</ref> and injured two others. The [[British Army|British army]] tried to censor his account on the grounds that it was too graphic. Senior officers, who were not at the scene, claimed the bomb was not inside the safe area.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/blast-that-killed-british-soldier-was-in-area-cleared-of-bombs-pmmlvh7979x|title=Blast that killed British soldier was in area cleared of bombs|date=2011-07-12|work=The Times|access-date=2019-11-01|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref>\n\n=== Kenya ===\nIn 2012 The Times posted Starkey to [[Nairobi|Nairobi, Kenya]] and appointed him [[Africa]] Correspondent.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessdailyafrica.com/news/The-Times-reporter-Jerome-Starkey-locked-up-/539546-3480806-ct79pm/index.html|title=British journalist held overnight at JKIA|last=Friday|last2=December 9|website=Business Daily|access-date=2019-11-01|last3=2016 16:10}}</ref>\n\nHe was deported from Nairobi in 2017<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.ug/british-journalist-detained-without-charge-kenya/|title=British journalist deported from Kenya|last=Independent|first=The|date=2016-12-10|website=The Independent Uganda|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://westminsterworld.com/award-winning-british-journalist-deported-from-kenya-after-unexplained-detention/|title=Award-winning British journalist deported from Kenya after unexplained detention|date=2016-12-12|website=Westminster World|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-11-01}}</ref> as a result of his work. The government of [[Uhuru Kenyatta]] gave no official explanation.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/times-reporter-deported-from-nairobi-after-night-in-cell-q7ph88fwc|title=Kenya expels Times reporter after night in cells|newspaper=The Times|language=en|access-date=2019-11-01|date=10 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\nStarkey won the [[Frontline Club]] award for excellence<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.journalism.co.uk/news-events-awards/times-afghanistan-correspondent-wins-frontline-club-excellence-award/s14/a541626/|title=Times Afghanistan correspondent wins Frontline Club excellence award|publisher=|date=22 November 2010}}</ref> in 2010, and the [[Kurt Schork]] memorial prize in 2011.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://iwpr.net/raise-awareness/winners-2011-kurt-schork-awards |title=Archived copy |access-date=9 November 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130604184728/http://iwpr.net/raise-awareness/winners-2011-kurt-schork-awards |archive-date=4 June 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>http://www.ksmfund.org/files/newsrelease-2011-winners.pdf</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n<!--- After listing your sources please cite them using inline citations and place them after the information they cite. Please see [[WP:REFB]] for instructions on how to add citations. --->\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Starkey, Jerome}}\n[[Category:British war correspondents]]\n[[Category:British male journalists]]\n[[Category:The Times people]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2011}}\n'''Jerome Starkey''' (born 1981, [[London]]) is an [[English people|English]] [[journalist]], [[Documentary film|broadcaster]] and [[motivational speaker]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.alternatives.org.uk/event/co-founder-extinction-rebellion-dna-skeena-rathor-multi-speaker-event-navigating-through|title=Co-founder of the Extinction Rebellion DNA - Skeena Rathor in multi speaker event - Navigating through an urgent time of change|last=UK|first=Alternatives|date=2019-11-12|website=www.alternatives.org.uk|language=en|access-date=2019-11-18}}</ref> best known for covering [[war]]s and the [[Natural environment|environment]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.frontlineclub.com/awards2010/|title=2010|website=Frontline Club|language=en|access-date=2019-11-01}}</ref> He challenged [[United States Armed Forces|US forces]] over [[Civilian casualties in the war in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|civilian casualties]] in [[Afghanistan|Afghanistsan]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2010/03/27/nato-tries-to-silence-jou_n_515652.html|title=NATO Tries To Silence Journalist Jerome Starkey Over Afghan Slayings (VIDEO)|date=2010-05-26|website=HuffPost UK|language=en|access-date=2019-11-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.niemanwatchdog.org/index.cfm?backgroundid=00440&fuseaction=background.view|title=U.S.-led forces in Afghanistan are committing atrocities, lying, and getting away with it|publisher=}}</ref> and was deported from [[Kenya]] in 2017<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mobile.nation.co.ke/news/Police-deport-British-journalist-/1950946-3481188-7ojd43z/index.html|title=Police deport British journalist Jerome Starkey|last=App|first=Daily Nation|website=mobile.nation.co.ke|language=en|access-date=2019-11-01}}</ref> after reporting on state-sponsored [[corruption]] and [[Extrajudicial killing|extra-judicial killings]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/kenyan-beauty-spot-blighted-by-all-the-bodies-washing-up-h3vq8v39f|title=Kenyan beauty spot blighted by 'all the bodies washing up'|last=|first=|date=15 July 2016|newspaper=The Times|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=1 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nStarkey grew up in [[London]] and won an academic [[scholarship]] to attend [[Stowe School]] in Buckinghamshire.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.telegraphindia.com/india/struck-by-a-rocket-that-killed-his-brother-boy-brings-out-the-best-in-man/cid/324792|title=Struck by a rocket that killed his brother, boy brings out the best in man|website=www.telegraphindia.com|language=en|access-date=2019-11-01}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nAfter graduating from [[Newcastle University]] with a degree in [[English literature]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.questia.com/newspaper/1G1-106280707/an-extra-degree-of-debt|title=\"An Extra Degree of Debt\" - The Journal (Newcastle, England), August 5, 2003 {{!}} Online Research Library: Questia|website=www.questia.com|access-date=2019-11-01}}</ref> he joined [[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]] in 2003 as a gradaute trainee.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.standard.co.uk/lifestyle/esmagazine/despatches-from-the-front-line-6451466.html|title=Despatches from the front line|date=2011-10-07|website=Evening Standard|language=en|access-date=2019-11-01}}</ref>\n\n=== Afghanistan ===\nIn 2006 he moved to [[Kabul]], Afghanistan to write [[propaganda]] for [[NATO|Nato]]'s [[International Security Assistance Force]]<ref name=\"Satterlee\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2008/jun/09/afghanistan-nato|title=Dispatches from the Afghan front|last=Satterlee|first=Saundra|date=2008-06-09|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-11-01|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> (Isaf). He served with the Combined Joint [[Psychological warfare|Psy-Ops]] Taskforce (CJPOTF) which produced a fortnightly newspaper called ''Sada-e Azadi'', or Voice of Freedom in [[Dari language|Dari]]. He resigned after six months, complaining that the newspaper was \"terrible\".<ref name=\"Satterlee\"/> Later he wrote in [[The Times]] how ''Sada-e Azadi'' was sold by the kilogram as scrap before it could reach readers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/natos-voice-is-stifled-as-propaganda-newspaper-ends-up-as-food-wrapping-td3dcwl2jcv|title=Nato's voice is stifled as propaganda newspaper ends up as food wrapping|last=story|first=Jerome Starkey: Behind the|date=2009-11-12|work=The Times|access-date=2019-11-01|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref>\n\nStarkey returned to Kabul as a [[Freelancer|freelance journalist]]. From 2008 until 2010 he worked for a range of broadcasters and newspapers including [[Sky News]], [[France 24]], ''[[The Scotsman]]'' and ''[[The Independent]]''. At ''[[The Independent]]'' he led a successful campaign to free a student journalist<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/free-at-last-student-in-hiding-after-karzais-intervention-1782909.html|title=Free at last: Student in hiding after Karzai's intervention|author=Kim Sengupta in Kabul|date=22 October 2011|work=The Independent}}</ref> [[Sayed Pervez Kambaksh]], who had been sentenced to death for [[blasphemy]].\n\n==== Civilian Casualties ====\nStarkey claimed that he was [[Blacklisting|black-listed]] by the military in Afghanistan as a result of his work on civilian casualties.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stripes.com/blogs/ombudsman/ombudsman-1.8931/reporter-complains-of-blacklisting-in-afghanistan-1.8946|title=Reporter complains of blacklisting in Afghanistan|work=Stars and Stripes}}</ref><ref>http://www.truth-out.org/where-are-this-wars-heroes-military-and-journalistic57406</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/robert-greenwald/rethink-afghanistan-why-i_b_527439.html#|title=Rethink Afghanistan: Independent Media Stands Up to Pentagon Propaganda|date=6 April 2010|work=The Huffington Post}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010 his investigation into a [[Night raid on Narang|Night Raid on Narang]], in Kunar Province, eastern Afghanistan, led [[International Security Assistance Force|NATO\u2019s International Security Assistance Force]] to admit it had killed eight schoolboys by mistake.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/nato-admits-that-deaths-of-8-boys-were-a-mistake-6hbmv3ljmj6|title=Nato admits that deaths of 8 boys were a mistake|last=Kabul|first=Jerome Starkey|date=2010-02-25|work=The Times|access-date=2019-11-01|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref>\n\nThe previous year he linked the newly formed [[United States Marine Corps Forces Special Operations Command|Marine Special Operations Command]] (MASROC) to three of the worst civilian casualty incidents in Afghanistan's recent history<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/news/world/asia/rumsfelds-renegade-unit-blamed-for-afghan-deaths-1685704.html|title=Rumsfeld's renegade unit blamed for Afghan deaths|date=2009-05-16|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2019-11-01}}</ref> including the [[Granai airstrike|Granai Airstrike]] in [[Bala Baluk massacre|Bala Balouk]], the [[Azizabad airstrike|Azizabad Airstrike]] in [[Herat Province|Herat province]] and the [[2007 Shinwar shooting|Shinwar Massacre]] in [[Nangarhar Province|Nangahar province]].\n\n===== Gardez night raid =====\nIn 2010, together with his colleagues Shoib Najafizada and Jeremy Kelly, Starkey exposed a [[cover-up]] by [[United States Army Special Forces|US Special Forces]] after an operation known as the [[Raid on Khataba]]<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/news/world/afghanistan/article7092604.ece|title=Login|publisher=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theintercept.com/2016/06/01/pentagon-special-ops-killing-of-pregnant-afghan-women-was-appropriate-use-of-force/|title=Pentagon: Special Ops Killing of Pregnant Afghan Women Was \"Appropriate\" Use of Force: Pentagon: Special Ops Killing of Pregnant Afghan Women Was \"Appropriate\" Use of Force|last=Scahill|first=Jeremy|date=2016-06-01|website=The Intercept|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/afghans-us-troops-covered-up-civilian-deaths/|title=Afghans: U.S. Troops \"Covered-Up\" Civilian Deaths|website=www.cbsnews.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/nato-covered-up-botched-night-raid-in-afghanistan-that-killed-five-fc9n5g92gbj|title=Nato 'covered up' botched night raid in Afghanistan that killed five|last=Khataba|first=Jerome Starkey|date=2010-03-13|work=The Times|access-date=2019-11-01|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref> which inspired the [[Academy Awards|Oscar]]-nominated documentary [[Dirty Wars]].\n\nDuring the raid, on 12 February 2010, unidentified special forces soldiers killed five innocent people including two pregnant women, a teenage girl engaged to be married and two brothers who worked for the local government in [[Paktia Province|Paktia]] province in [[Eastern Afghanistan Operations|eastern Afghanistan]].<ref name=\":0\" /> All of the victims were from the same family. Initially the soldiers said the women were victims of a triple [[Honor killing|honour killing]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://afghanistan.blogs.cnn.com/2010/02/12/bound-gagged-bodies-of-women-found/|title=Bodies believed to be 'honor killing' victims|language=en|access-date=2019-11-01}}</ref> They said they discovered the women's bodies \"tied up, gagged and killed\"<ref name=\"dvidshub.net\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.dvidshub.net/news/45240/joint-force-operating-gardez-makes-gruesome-discovery|title=Joint force operating in Gardez makes gruesome discovery|website=DVIDS|language=en|access-date=2019-11-01}}</ref> and that the dead men were [[Insurgency|insurgents]].<ref name=\"dvidshub.net\"/>\n\nWhen Starkey challenged Nato's account they accused him of lying.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.military-world.net/Afghanistan/3502.html | title=ISAF Rejects Cover up Allegation &#124; Military-World Website}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/04/06/world/asia/06afghan.html|title=Afghan Investigators Say U.S. Troops Tried to Cover Up Evidence in Botched Raid|last=Jr|first=Richard A. Oppel|date=2010-04-05|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-11-01|last2=Wafa|first2=Abdul Waheed|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> However, four weeks later [[William H. McRaven]], the commander of America's [[Joint Special Operations Command]] ([[Joint Special Operations Command|JSOC]]), admitted his soldiers were resopnsible.<ref name=\"Gardez\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/us-army-chief-begs-afghans-to-forgive-k9lkmmr5cjx|title=US army chief begs Afghans to forgive|last=Gardez|first=Jerome Starkey, Khataba|date=2010-04-09|work=The Times|access-date=2019-11-01|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref> [[William H. McRaven|McRaven]] travelled to the family's compound, outside [[Gardez]] and offered to sacrifice a sheep outside their door in a ritual act of [[Nanawatai]], to seek their forgiveness.<ref name=\"Gardez\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://abcnews.go.com/WN/Afghanistan/special-forces-apologize-afghan-civilian-deaths-sheep/story?id=10320603|title=Apologizing for Afghan Deaths With Sheep?|website=ABC News|language=en|access-date=2019-11-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.csmonitor.com/World/Asia-South-Central/2010/0408/US-military-offers-sheep-in-apology-for-Afghanistan-deaths|title=US military offers sheep in apology for Afghanistan deaths|date=2010-04-08|work=Christian Science Monitor|access-date=2019-11-01|issn=0882-7729}}</ref>\n\n==== Close calls ====\nIn 2010, Jerome was nearly killed during an [[Embedded journalism|embed]] with British troops in [[Helmand Province]] when an [[Improvised explosive device]] (IED) exploded fewer than 10 metres in front of him.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thetimes.co.uk/tto/news/world/asia/afghanistan/article2775671.ece|title=Final, fatal step of 'a really brilliant bloke'|newspaper=The Times|date=21 October 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/top-stories/2010/10/22/30-feet-from-the-brutal-reality-of-the-afghan-war-death-of-a-soldier-115875-22650096/|title=30 feet from the brutal reality of the Afghan war: Death of a soldier|author=mirror Administrator|date=22 October 2010|work=mirror}}</ref> The explosion, inside a designated safe area which had recently been cleared by the [[Royal Engineers]], killed Corporal David Barnsdale<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mod.uk/DefenceInternet/DefenceNews/MilitaryOperations/CorporalDavidBarnsdaleKilledInAfghanistan.htm|title=Corporal David Barnsdale killed in Afghanistan|publisher=}}</ref> and injured two others. The [[British Army|British army]] tried to censor his account on the grounds that it was too graphic. Senior officers, who were not at the scene, claimed the bomb was not inside the safe area.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/blast-that-killed-british-soldier-was-in-area-cleared-of-bombs-pmmlvh7979x|title=Blast that killed British soldier was in area cleared of bombs|date=2011-07-12|work=The Times|access-date=2019-11-01|language=en|issn=0140-0460}}</ref>\n\n=== Kenya ===\nIn 2012 The Times posted Starkey to [[Nairobi|Nairobi, Kenya]] and appointed him [[Africa]] Correspondent.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessdailyafrica.com/news/The-Times-reporter-Jerome-Starkey-locked-up-/539546-3480806-ct79pm/index.html|title=British journalist held overnight at JKIA|last=Friday|last2=December 9|website=Business Daily|access-date=2019-11-01|last3=2016 16:10}}</ref>\n\nHe was deported from Nairobi in 2017<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.ug/british-journalist-detained-without-charge-kenya/|title=British journalist deported from Kenya|last=Independent|first=The|date=2016-12-10|website=The Independent Uganda|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://westminsterworld.com/award-winning-british-journalist-deported-from-kenya-after-unexplained-detention/|title=Award-winning British journalist deported from Kenya after unexplained detention|date=2016-12-12|website=Westminster World|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-11-01}}</ref> as a result of his work. The government of [[Uhuru Kenyatta]] gave no official explanation.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/times-reporter-deported-from-nairobi-after-night-in-cell-q7ph88fwc|title=Kenya expels Times reporter after night in cells|newspaper=The Times|language=en|access-date=2019-11-01|date=10 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Awards ==\nStarkey won the [[Frontline Club]] award for excellence<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.journalism.co.uk/news-events-awards/times-afghanistan-correspondent-wins-frontline-club-excellence-award/s14/a541626/|title=Times Afghanistan correspondent wins Frontline Club excellence award|publisher=|date=22 November 2010}}</ref> in 2010, and the [[Kurt Schork]] memorial prize in 2011.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://iwpr.net/raise-awareness/winners-2011-kurt-schork-awards |title=Archived copy |access-date=9 November 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130604184728/http://iwpr.net/raise-awareness/winners-2011-kurt-schork-awards |archive-date=4 June 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>http://www.ksmfund.org/files/newsrelease-2011-winners.pdf</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n<!--- After listing your sources please cite them using inline citations and place them after the information they cite. Please see [[WP:REFB]] for instructions on how to add citations. --->\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Starkey, Jerome}}\n[[Category:British war correspondents]]\n[[Category:British male journalists]]\n[[Category:The Times people]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:1981 births]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jerome_Starkey"}
